<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Anthony Cartmell (CYS0042)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:2.85pt 0pt 8.8pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Anthony </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cartmell</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (CYS0042)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:2.85pt 0pt 8.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I have cycled as a long-distance tourist for 30 years, and now have a family who love cycling if only they could find safe places to ride their bikes. We try to use bicycles as much as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> possible for local trips, but often are forced to use the car to stay safe.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold"> 1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Whether cycling is safe, particularly in towns and cities.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> 1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Quick answer: No, cycling is not safe in the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 1.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cycling is statistically safe, in that relatively few people get killed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> or seriously injured riding their bikes. BUT cycling in the UK is subjectively extremely dangerous: it's an activity that apparently needs specialist clothing, protective equipment, and detailed training.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 1.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The apparent danger is not helped by regular near-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">misses, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">punishment passes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">from impatient motorists who think cyclists should be banned from our roads. Cyclists are a minority out-group, and as such are demonised in the press at every opportunity: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cyclists should get off the roads</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">goes hand-in-ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nd with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cyclists should get off the pavements</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 1.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">As a keen cyclist, I take my children to school on a trailer bicycle behind my bike. We are now the only family in a school of 400 pupils to use bicycles to get to school. The school actively discourage peop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">le from cycling, and we too would not dream of encouraging others to follow our example. The local roads are just too frightening to cycle along, even for experts like me.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold"> 2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">What central and local Government could do to improve cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">safety.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> 2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Quick answer: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">provide well-designed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> in addition to footways and carriageways on our roads, just as the Dutch do.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 2.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Back in the late 1800's when bicycles were deemed to be more like carriages than pedestrians, cyclists were required to ride in the carriageway. In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> modern times, cyclists put themselves are risk of serious injury and death by riding in the carriageway amongst cars and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Which is why many flout the law, making themselves criminals, by riding on the footway.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Of course the footways are not design</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ed for cycling, and this annoys pedestrians. We need an in-between way: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. Such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> can be used by people on bicycles, people in faster mobility scooters, people on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Segways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, and other forms of personal transport that aren't safe on carriagewa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ys.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 2.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Government need to plan strategically for cycling. Here in West Sussex they have abolished the post of Cycling Officer, have dropped any pretence that they have a Cycling Strategy, and have devolved highways decision-making to such a low level th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">at it's now impossible for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> between adjacent towns to be even considered.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 2.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should be designed as if they were half-scale roads for motor vehicles. They should be direct, coherent, safe, and should not have obstructions in the middle of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">em!</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 2.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To have any chance at all of gaining the benefits in safety and community that the Dutch enjoy, we need to be investing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">£</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">40 per person per year, over a decade or more, specifically in building </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. Long-term leadership and long-term investment ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e crucial if any change is to be made. If we don't invest, then the inevitable result will be more people cycling (as fuel costs rise) and more people being killed and seriously injured in collisions with motor vehicles.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold"> 3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Whether it would be desirable and f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">easible to segregate cyclists from other road users, including, for example, by prohibiting HGVs from entering city centres at peak hours.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> 3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Quick answer: Yes, both desirable and feasible. Segregate cyclists from motor vehicles both in space and time, just a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s the Dutch do.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 3.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cycling is a mode of transport that has the potential to solve many of our urban problems: pollution, congestion, road danger, lack of exercise, lack of community. Cycling should therefore be prioritised in planning and funding over less-ef</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ficient modes of transport such as private motor vehicles.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 3.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">HGVs have no place in busy city streets. Unless they really are essential, they should be replaced by smaller vehicles delivering locally from out-of-town distribution centres.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 3.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We need to decide wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">at our roads and streets are for, and design them to meet their chosen functions. Major roads should allow HGV </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, but should have completely segregated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. Local streets should be blocked to through motor traffic, have 20mph speed limits, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on-street cycle lanes as needed. We should stop trying to have roads that simultaneously try to be cycle routes, motorways, shopping streets and residential streets all at the same time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold"> 4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Other ideas for improving cycling safety would also be welcomed.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> 4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Quic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">k answer: don't try to increase safety, work to reduce or remove the danger.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 4.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cycling is intrinsically safe. What is not safe is being forced to cycle in amongst heavy and fast-moving motor vehicles. Stop blaming cyclists, stop asking them to wear high-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">viz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and helmets, stop victim-blaming. Focus efforts on reducing road danger from motor vehicles, rather than trying to increase safety of vulnerable road users in the face of ever-increasing road danger.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 4.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Forget about adding mirrors and sensors to some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> There will always be lorry drivers who accidentally fail to look in their mirrors, and sensors that will fail to detect cyclists about to be killed. Instead focus on sustainable safety, but keeping cyclists and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> apart from each other at all times. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Then the inevitable human failings will be much less likely to result in death or serious injury.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 4.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Real-world research has already been carried out into all these aspects of cycling safety, and well-developed and proven solutions are already available. You </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">only need to travel to a country that's nearer London than Scotland is, and where the people speak pretty good English, to see these solutions in action. Safety is when people aged 8 to 80 are free and happy to use bicycles for local transport in towns and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> cities.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 4.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sign up for a Study Tour in the Netherlands from David </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Hembrow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (an English expatriate who knows all there is about cycle provision) and it will all become very clear what needs to be done, and how to do it.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:2.85pt 0pt 8.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:2.85pt 0pt 8.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>